topic.title: Performance Monitor Command

body.p: MRPC Command ID: 0x07
Performance Monitor (PMON) provides 3 types of counters:

Bandwidth counters provide per-port byte counts for Posted, Non-posted and Completion type TLPs for both ingress and egress traffic directions. Bandwidth is either reported in terms of RAW bandwidth or PAYLOAD bandwidth:

li.p: RAW Bandwidth - This counts TLPs with headers included (header sizes vary dependent on addressing scheme (2DW or 3DW)
PAYLOAD Bandwidth - This counts only the payload portion of the TLP and ignores any framing or headers

body.p: The time interval of these TLPs going through the port is also recorded, allowing calculation of the bandwidth on a per-port basis. The TLP byte counters are 32 bits counters but the user has an option to accumulate them to 64 bit counters by setting the Accumulate byte count in FW field to 1 in the ChipLink.

There are 64 event counters in each stack. Each counter indexed from 0-63 is configured via ingress event mask parameter and port mask parameter. When the mask bit for a particular event is set, that counter is updated when that event type is detected, and only if the accompanying port number is enabled via the associated port mask parameter. Each event counter can count only 1 event at the same time. The supported events are: AER errors, routing rule match events and NAK indications from DLL/PL. Before setting up the event counter, sub command 8, 9, 10, or 11 should be used first to setup the Routing Rule for counting routing rule match events.

Each counter can also be configured to accumulate good P/NP/CP TLPs in both the ingress and egress directions â€“ that is, packets that are not marked nullify or discard. Note that the ingress and egress direction selection is only supported for P/NP/CP TLP accumulation. Other event monitors only support counting ingress TLPs.
Each port also supports a latency counter to count the tlp routing latency inside the switch from different source port. The recorded routing latency is composed by 3 part of 3 parts:
1. Routing latency from ingress physical port to switch core: depends on the link width and link rate of ingress source port

table.title: ingress port routing latency(ns)

body.p: 2. Routing latency inside switch core: auto record records when a new tlp is routed from ingress port to egress port through the switch core. This part maybe counter can be 0 if no TLP has been routed to the specified egress port ever or since the last clear.
3. Routing latency from switch core to egress physical port: depends on the link width and link rate of egress destination port

table.title: egress port routing latency(ns)

body.p: Latency The latency counter can be setup in two mays ways:
1. Single Latency Path: from fixed source port to a fixed destination port
2. Multiple Latency Path: from all active port ports to a fixed destination port

The latency counter output counters provides a 16 bit maximum latency field and a 16 bit minimum latency field. For the Single Latency Patch, those two Path, the min and max latency fields are the same, which all are so the sum of 3 latency part since both the ingress port and egress port the 3 latency parts is fixed. For the Multiple Latency Path, since the ingress port is not fixed, the worst ingress latency path from the all the active possible ingress port will be selected to get the maximum latency, and the best ingress latency path will be selected to get the minimum latency.

As multiple MRPC hosts and the Firmware CLI are all able to access PMON the performance monitor (PMON), there is an internal access permission mechanism to prevent conflicts. When one host or Firmware CLI is accessing PMON, other hosts or Firmware CLI cannot access PMON until the host or Firmware CLI releases the access permission. The access permission acquisition and release are automatic. If access to PMON is refused, the access attempt can simply be retried after a delay.

body.p: This sub command is used to search the RST CAMs entry for TLPs target error hole in PCIe memory space or ID space managed by Switch USP but expected no transaction.

section.p: This field should be 8 to perform event counting for error TLP routing rule match.
For address routing, error TLP routing means the target address of the TLP hit the hole of address range managed by USP.
For ID routing, error TLP routing means the Requester ID of Completion TLP hit the hole of ID range managed by USP.
Stack Number.
Partition Number.
â€œ0â€ means Transparent mode. â€œ1â€ means Non-Transparent mode.

ul.li: â€œ0â€ indicates Address Routing defined in PCIe Spec.
â€œ1â€ indicates ID Routing defined in PCIe Spec.
â€œ1â€ means each received TLP target error hole will increment the count of the event counter selected by EVENT_CNTR_IDX.
â€œ0â€ means disable this Routing Rule match to add the count by 1.

section.p: This field indicates which event counter to increment by 1 when the TLP match on the selected routing rule.

topic.title: Performance Monitor â€”Command Example

ol.li:
Read Bandwidth Counter
Read bandwidth counters of port 16 and 40 with read clear enabled
Write address 0 with data: 0x01100201 0x0128
Write address 2048 with data: 7
Read return data, time interval take 2 DWs, each port take 12 DWs, so totally read 26 DWs
Read at address 1024 for 26 DWs data

Setup Event Counter
event counter#6, port mask 0x01, event type mask 0x00000001, egress, threshold 0x100000: counter 6 will monitor UR error event for port 0 in the egress direction.
event counter#7, port mask 0x01, event type mask 0x00100000, ingress, threshold 0x300: counter 7 will monitor Posted TLP received event for port 0 in the ingress direction.
Write address 0 with data: 0x02060000 0x00000101 0x10000080 0x00000100 0x03000010 0x0000
Write address 2048 with data: 7

Read Event Counter
Read 8 event counters(counter 0 ~ 7) of stack 0 with read not clear option.
Write address 0 with data: 0x08000002 0x00000000
Write address 2048 with data: 7
Read return data, 8 counters take 16 DWs
Read at address 1024 for 16 DWs data

Dump Event Counter setup
Dump the setup information of 8 continuous event counter(counter 0 ~ 7) of stack 0
Write address 0 with data: 0x08000003
Write address 2048 with data: 7
Read return data, 8 counters take 72 Bytes, so read 18 DWs
Read at address 1024 for 18 DWs data

Setup Latency Counter
Setup the latency counter of port 0 and port 40 to monitor the latency from all source port
Write address 0 with data: 0x3f000204 0x00003f28
Write address 2048 with data: 7

Dump Latency Counter setup
Dump the setup information of latency counter of port 0 and port 40
Write address 0 with data: 0x28000205
Write address 2048 with data: 7
Read return data, One port takes 1 byte, there're 2 ports so read 1 DW
Read at address 1024 for 1 DW data

Read Latency Counter
Read the latency counter of port 0 and port 40 with read not clear option
Write address 0 with data: 0x00000206 0x00000028
Write address 2048 with data: 7
Read return data, 2 ports, per port takes 1 DW, so read 2 DWs
Read at address 1024 for 2 DWs data

Error TLP Routing Rule match for PMON event counting
Setup the event counter 24 of stack 3 to monitor the Error TLPs that routed to non-prefetch memory space hole of partition 1 through ingress port of stack 3
Write address 0 with data: 0x00010308 0x18010200
Write address 2048 with data: 7

Implicit TLP Routing Rule match for PMON event counting
Setup the event counter 15 of stack 0 to monitor the CFG TLPs routing to partition 0 through ingress port of stack 0
Write address 0 with data: 0x01000009 0x0f
Write address 2048 with data: 7

TLP routing to USP Rule Match for PMON event counting
Setup the event counter 44 of stack 0 to monitor the P/NP memory TLPs come out from the USP of partition 0 through ingress port of stack 0
Write address 0 with data: 0x0000000a 0x2c01
Write address 2048 with data: 7

TLP routing to DSP Rule Match for PMON event counting
Setup the event counter 33 of stack 2 to monitor the Prefetch memory TLPs come out from the logical port 2 of partition 1 through ingress port of stack 2.
Write address 0 with data: 0x0201020b 0x21010100
Write address 2048 with data: 7
